lk, negedge clk)` block because `tb_match` was false, even though the specific component mismatches were zero. \n9. In the `always` block (lines 265-286), `stats1.errors++` is called if `!tb_match`. Since the mismatch count for specific signals (pm, hh, mm, ss) is 0, the mismatch is purely in the global `stats1.errors`. This happens because `tb_match` is evaluated at the start of simulation (time 0) or during the first transition, and if the DUT and Reference have different initial values (e.g., one is 0 and the other is X), `tb_match` will be false, triggering the error count.\n10. Since the RTL and the functional requirements are satisfied (all individual outputs are correct), the error is a false positive in the testbench's error-counting logic at time 0.",
